<h1>@HI{{nara}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vplain{{}} (@HI{{no}}) @EM{{@HI{{nara}}}}
<li> @Ai{{}} (@HI{{no}}) @EM{{@HI{{nara}}}}
<li> @Anastem{{}} (@HI{{no}}) @EM{{@HI{{nara}}}}
<li> @N{{}} (@HI{{no}}) @EM{{@HI{{nara}}}}
</ol>
</dl>

<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
When a speaker wishes to take up a topic introduced by another person and give some information,
@N{{}}@EM{{@HI{{nara}}}} is used.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{@KJ{{warm^spring}}ni @KJ{{going}}kitaindesuga, dokoka ii @KJ{{place}}arimasenka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{@KJ{{warm^spring}}@EM{{nara}}, @KJ{{white^horse}}ga ii desu yo.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: I'd like to visit a hot spring resort. Don't you know a good place?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: If you're talking about hot spring resorts, Hakuba would be good.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@EM{{@HI{{nara}}}} is a conjunction that indicates that the preceding sentence is the
speaker's supposition or the actualisation of something in the future.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{shikago}}he@KJ{{going}}kuno@EM{{nara}}@KT{{basu}}de@KJ{{going}}kinasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      If you go to Chicago, go by bus.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
A major difference between @EM{{@HI{{nara}}}} and <a href="grammar-tara.html">@HI{{tara}}</a> is that 
the clause following @EM{{@HI{{nara}}}} expresses what will definitely happen if the supposed event takes place
whereas that following @HI{{tara}} expresses what would "happen to" take place.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{ride}}ru@EM{{nara}}@KJ{{drink}}muna. @KJ{{drink}}ndara@KJ{{ride}}runa.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      If you (are going to) drive, don't drink. If you have been drinking, don't drive.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{nara}}}} is the simplified form of @HI{{naraba}}, the conditional form of the copula @HI{{da}}.
In modern Japanese, however, the @HI{{ba}} is usually omitted.
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{nara}}}} requires a noun or noun equivalent. So if the preceding element is not a noun, it is
nominalised by @HI{{no}}. However, in modern Japanese this @HI{{no}} is optional. In conversation, this @HI{{no}}
can become @HI{{nn}}.
</p>

